Poor Cook, can't win. Cook I think your last post was clear and concise, and your football rules an excellant way of describing your experience and probably the entire war. Then along comes Tom and slaps you alongside the head.  <br><br>
Regarding on ramp bums, as I call them, I encourage all to not &quot;feed the animals&quot;. Most are phony and it only encourages them to duck being responsible and getting a job and paying taxes etc. etc.<br><br>
As to Randy Caudill, the Marine deserter, I am shocked to say that I am of opinion different than Cooks, who is quite liberal on this situation.  This was an enlisted Marine, with almost one year in. If he was a coward, scared, or just did not want to go to Nam, he could have declared himself a C.O. - yes you can do that even if in the military - and stood his ground. Odds are he would get some brig time, but also be able to walk away with his head held high and up. Instead he deserted. He snuck away to Canada.  I agree with you, Cook, (surprise #4) that he took advantage of the USA and frequently crossed back and forth to visit, etc.  The question is now, what do you do with a deserter 30 years later?  Forgive him and you make an example of him for future deserters.  Was he a coward and just scared, or did he have a change of heart, a soulfull change in moral conviction about war and killing? (I doubt it).  I hope there is some military proceedings so at least we can hear him talk, or read about it. I heard today he was charged with the lessor of desertion charges, and probably will only get a less than honorable discharge if he accepts.  (Be a fool not to).<br><br>
Lastly, you and Art think that I am flip flopping. You added to gain acceptance. Rest easy, I don't need acceptance (and the many hits I have got on this site should prove that) and perhaps flip floppin is the sound of one's mind changing due to new thinking or additional information.  Or maybe it just is the sound of my sandles flip floppin' away....<br>

